@node "WARNUNG" "Warnings"
@next "NEUES"

 @{b}Warnings@{ub}
 ========

 @{b}NOTE!@{ub}
 Working with files is a constant source of risk. Remember
 that you use this piece of software on your own risk and be
 prepared to face a loss of data. Be sure to have a backup!

 Comment:
 Working without a backup is not careless, it's even worse.

 @{b}IMPORTANT!@{ub}
 Setting the application's stack too small will most
 certainly make your machine crash. You must set the stack
 to a reasonable size (8192 bytes is sufficient). Look at
 the stack size in the information window of the
 application's icon, and set the stack manually if you
 intend to start Peperoni via command line interface.

@endnode

@node "VORWORT" "Preface"
@next "RECHT"
@prev "WARNUNG"

 @{b}1 Preface@{ub}
 =========

 One of mankind's biggest mistake is the belief, a computer
 might be able to solve problems. Since the computer has
 become popular for home and office, solving one problem
 always created at least one new problem. For example,
 solving the problem of mass data by compressing it
 forced users to fiddle around with compression software.

 While looking for compression software for the Amiga,
 I made out the following categories:

 @{b}Spartans@{ub}
 Sparta is known for its ancient population which
 distinguished itself through discipline and austerity. It
 just fits for command line programs. These applications are
 likely to be called «powerful» by computer specialists and
 «user-hostile» by everyone else.

 @{b}Exotics@{ub}
 There are many programs which seem to be made for special
 tasks or archiving formats nobody ever heard of. Such
 applications offer packing ARJ plus depacking LZX or
 transforming LHA into a dialect of ZOOed TAR by
 interpreting it as Tibetan and adding a smily sticker.

 @{b}Tuners@{ub}
 Unfortunately I couldn't make up a better description for
 the sort of software which pops up a window with lots of
 colourful buttons and menues and basically does nothing but
 replacing the Spartan's keyboard brutality by a mouseclick
 orgy. Just like command line programs they insist on being
 told about the archive's format and where to put the result
 and they will surely not remember that you're always packing
 to «RAM:».

 Im not even trying to say Peperoni was ingenious or rulez or
 what else. As a frontend, it will not work without the
 Spartans. It does not support most of the original functions,
 and its requirements are comparably high for an Amiga
 frontend. Anyway, I got used to «StuffIt» (Mac) and wanted
 to bring similar features to the Amiga.

@endnode

