@node "VORAUS" "Requirements"
@next "INSTALL"
@prev "RECHT"

 @{b}3 Requirements@{ub}
 ==============

 Processor: 68020 or higher
 System:    OS 3.0 or higher
 @{"MUI" link "MUI" 0}:      V3 or higher
 Memory:    approx. 400K

 Additionally, you need the programs «LHA», «LZX», «ZIP»,
 and «UNZIP» which are not included in this package. These
 programs are available for free on various public domain
 series and from Aminet. I suppose they're already on your
 harddisk.

@endnode

@node "INSTALL" "Installation"
@next "BEDIENUNG"
@prev "VORAUS"

 @{b}4 Installation@{ub}
 ==============

 Installation is very easy, so I don't provide an Installer
 script. There are two versions of the program included,
 one is compiled for Amigas equipped with a 68020 CPU at
 least («Peperoni.020»), the other one is compiled for
 68040/060 CPUs only («Peperoni.040»):

 - Copy the appropriate version along with its icon file
   wherever you like.
 - Copy:
   · either the whole directory «Catalogs» to the same place
     as the application
   · or the appropriate catalog file into your
     «LOCALE:Catalogs/<language>/» directory, where
     <language> stands for the name of the language.

     The built-in language is German (sorry pals, most
     feedback came from Germany; and I live there, too).

 I do also provide two AppIcons which you may copy
 wherever you like, too. But I don't force anyone to use
 them, they're not even default.

@endnode

@node "BEDIENUNG" "Usage"
@next "STARTEN"
@prev "INSTALL"

 @{b}5 Usage@{ub}
 =======

 My primary aim was neither implementing all original
 functions of the supported compression formats nor building
 an almighty programmable system. If you need this, go
 and look somewhere else. I just wanted simplicity.

     5.1 @{" Getting Started " link "STARTEN" 0}
     5.2 @{" Changing the Preferences " link "VOREINST" 0}
     5.3 @{" Packing Files " link "PACKEN" 0}
     5.4 @{" Depacking Archives " link "ENTPACKEN" 0}
     5.5 @{" Quitting the Program " link "BEENDEN" 0}

@endnode

@node "STARTEN" "Getting Started"
@next "VOREINST"
@prev "BEDIENUNG"

 @{b}5.1 How to Run Peperoni@{ub}
 =======================

 You may start Peperoni either via @{"command line interface" link "AUFRUFEN" 0}
 (shell) or by double-clicking its icon on the Workbench. If
 you run it via shell, remember to set the stack size.

 Peperoni can be started only once. Why should anyone
 need multiple Peperonis flooding the Workbench with
 AppIcons? If you like Peperoni to be started at booting
 time, just put it into the directory «SYS:WBStartup/».

 It does not support a single command line parameter, it
 is no commodity, and don't dare to ask for an ARexx port.

@endnode

@node "VOREINST" "Change Preferences"
@next "PACKFORMAT"
@prev "STARTEN"

 @{b}5.2 Change Preferences@{ub}
 ======================

 Open the preferences window by double-clicking one of
 the AppIcons. The following actions are possible:

    General:
    @{"Set packing format" link "PACKFORMAT" 0}
    @{"Set destination directory" link "ZIELVERZ" 0}
    @{"Preserve or suppress path information" link "PFADINFO" 0}

    AppIcons:
    @{"Set AppIcon icon file" link "APPICONBILD" 0}
    @{"Change AppIcon label" link "APPICONLABEL" 0}
    @{"Set AppIcon position" link "APPICONPOS" 0}

    Programs:
    @{"Set program paths" link "EXTPROGPFAD" 0}
    @{"Set LZX/ZIP compression rate" link "KOMPRRATE" 0}

 The preferences window consists of three pages which
 contain user interface elements partioned in different
 sections.

 Basically, the preferences window provides four special
 buttons «Quit», «Save», «Use», and «Cancel». For all
 changes you make, remember:

 · @{b}Quit@{ub} quits the program, but does not save
   the preferences.
 · @{b}Save@{ub} writes the preferences to disk,
   applies them, and closes the preferences window.
 · @{b}Use@{ub} applies the preferences and closes the
   preferences window, but changes will be lost when
   as soon as you quit the program.
 · @{b}Cancel@{ub} closes the preferences window and
   drops all changes.

@endnode

@node "PACKFORMAT" "Set Packing Format"
@next "ZIELVERZ"
@prev "VOREINST"

 @{b}Set Packing Format@{ub}
 ==================

 -- Page «General», section «Packing»

 In order to have files packed, Peperoni has to know which
 packer to address. There are two ways of setting your
 favorite packing format:

 @{b}· Set a Fixed Format@{ub}

   If you mainly use a certain format, this setting is
   recommended.
   - Set the cycle gadget @{b}Format@{ub} to «LHA», «LZX»,
     or «ZIP»

 @{b}· Always Ask the Format@{ub}

   If you're like me and like to change the format rather
   often, why not use Peperoni's requester feature? With
   this option switched on, there's a requester window
   appearing before each packing procedure giving you the
   choice of format.

   - Set cycle gadget @{b}Format@{ub} to «Always ask»

@endnode

@node "ZIELVERZ" "Set Destination Directory"
@next "PFADINFO"
@prev "PACKFORMAT"

 @{b}Set Destination Directory@{ub}
 ========================

 -- Page «General», sections «Packing»/«Depacking»

 Packing creates new files as well as depacking does.
 As Peperoni needs to know where to put those files,
 there are two cycle gadgets labelled @{b}Target@{ub},
 one for packing and one for depacking. There are three
 different default targets you may choose:

 @{b}· Set Source Directory as Destination@{ub}

   You can tell Peperoni to create new files in the same
   directory where the source files are placed.

   - Set cycle gadget @{b}Target@{ub} to «Same directory»

   Hint: When packing several files placed in different
	 source directories, Peperoni uses the path of
	 the first file in its list as destination. I guess
	 that the AmigaOS sorts this list in the same order
	 as you selected the icons.

 @{b}· Always Ask the Destination Directory@{ub}

   If you like flexibility concerning the destination,
   you can make Peperoni open a filerequester for each
   packing or depacking procedure.

   - Set cycle gadget @{b}Target@{ub} to «Always ask»

   Hint: When packing, this option offers an additional
	 feature--you may specify a name for the archive
	 file. In any other case, a default name will be
	 used.

 @{b}· Set a Fixed Directory@{ub}

   If you prefer a certain destination for all packing
   or depacking procedures (think of RAM:), then I
   recommend to use this setting:

   - Set cycle gadget @{b}Target@{ub} to «Fixed directory»
     => String gadget and button below are activated
   - Choose a directory. Options:
     · Type full path into the string gadget
     · Click the button (pops up a filerequester) and
       select a directory using the filerequester

@endnode

@node "PFADINFO" "Preserve or Suppress Path Information"
@next "APPICONBILD"
@prev "ZIELVERZ"

 @{b}Preserve or Suppress Path Information@{ub}
 =====================================

 -- Page «General», sections «Packing»/«Depacking»

 For both packing and depacking, a file can be written
 either with its full path or with its name only. If you
 preserve path information, depacking does not only create
 files but also the original directory structure.

 @{b}· Preserve Path Information when Packing@{ub}

   Use this setting if you want path information of a file
   to be written along with its name into the archive:

   - Check checkbox @{b}Pack complete paths@{ub}

 @{b}· Preserve Path Information when depacking@{ub}

   This feature only works if an archive contains path
   information. Use this setting if you want to depack
   files with their original directory structure.

   - Check checkbox @{b}Depack complete paths@{ub}

 @{b}· Suppress Path Information when Packing or Depacking@{ub}

   Deactivate the corresponding setting if you want to
   prevent path information from being written when packing
   or depacking.

   - Uncheck checkbox @{b}Pack complete paths@{ub} or
     @{b}Depack complete paths@{ub} respectively

@endnode

@node "APPICONBILD" "Set AppIcon Icon File"
@next "APPICONLABEL"
@prev "APPICONPOS"

 @{b}Set AppIcon Icon File{ub}
 =====================

 -- Page «AppIcons», sections «Packing AppIcon»/
    «Depacking AppIcon»

 By default, Peperoni uses its own icon file («Peperoni.info»)
 for both AppIcons. In order to change the look, you don't
 have to edit this icon file. Instead, you can use any
 icon file you like--one for both AppIcons or a seperate one
 for each AppIcon.

 @{b}· Set Icon File for Packing AppIcon or Depacking AppIcon@{ub}

   Setup works the same way for both AppIcons, you
   just have to use the interface elements of the appropriate
   section. There are two ways of choosing a specific icon
   file:

   The comfortable way first:
   - Click button next to «File» string gadget (pops up a
     filerequester) and select a file using the
     filerequester.

   Now for the less comfortable way:
   - Type in full path of the icon file (including drive
     information) into the string gaget labelled «File»

@endnode

@node "APPICONLABEL" "Change AppIcon Label"
@next "APPICONPOS"
@prev "APPICONBILD"

 @{b}Change AppIcon Label@{ub}
 ====================

 -- Page «AppIcons», sections «Packing AppIcon»/
    «Depacking AppIcon»

 By default, AppIcons are labelled «Packing» and «Depacking»
 respectively. Since version 1.5b, you may change these
 labels--to a string with up to 30 characters (don't use
 quotation marks!).

 @{b}· Change Label of the Packing AppIcon or Depacking AppIcon@{ub}

   Setup works the same way for both AppIcons, you just
   have to use the interface elements of the appropriate
   section.

   - Type desired label into string gadget @{b}Label@{ub}

@endnode

@node "APPICONPOS" "Set AppIcon Position"
@next "EXTPROGPFAD"
@prev "APPICONLABEL"

 @{b}Set AppIcon Position@{ub}
 ====================

 -- Page «AppIcons», sections «Packing AppIcon»/
    «Depacking AppIcon»

 By default, and for the coordinates 0/0, the AppIcon
 position is set by the AmigaOS--like the icon of an
 inserted floppy disk. As this will not please anyone,
 you may set coordinates.

 @{b}· Set Position of the Packing AppIcon or Depacking AppIcon@{ub}

  Setup works the same way for both AppIcons, you just
  have to use the interface elements of the appropriate
  section. Coordinates start counting at 0 at the
  upper and left screen border. There are two different
  ways of setting coordinates.

  The comfortable way first:
  - Click button @{b}Position@{ub}
    => Small window pops up
  - Drag small window to desired position
  - Close small window
    => Coordinates are written into string gadgets
       @{b}X@{ub} and @{b}Y@{ub} automatically

  Now for the less comfortable way:
  - Type in the X coordinate into string gadget @{b}X@{ub}
  - Type in the Y coordinate into string gadget @{b}Y@{ub}

  Hint: If you type in coordinates exceeding the screen's
	measurement, the AppIcon position is set by the
	AmigaOS.

@endnode

@node "EXTPROGPFAD" "Set Program Paths"
@next "KOMPRATE"
@prev "APPICONPOS"

 @{b}Set Program Paths@{ub}
 =================

 -- Page «Programs»

 As Peperoni calls the external programs LHA, LZX, ZIP,
 and UNZIP, it needs to know where they are. The
 easiest way is to include them into the command path,
 making them visible for all the system.
 Setup works the same way for all external programs, you
 just have to use the interface elements of the appropriate
 section.

 @{b}· If a Program is Included in the Command Path@{ub}

   By default, the command path includes the directories
   SYS:C, SYS:Utilities, SYS:Tools, SYS:System, SYS:Rexxc,
   SYS:S, SYS:Prefs, SYS:WBStartup, and
   SYS:Tools/Commodities as well as all directories you
   add using the AmigaDOS command PATH.

   - Check checkbox @{b}Program in command path@{ub}
     => String gadget and button below are deactivated

 @{b}· If a Program is Not Included in the Command Path@{ub}

   You don't have to fill up your C: directory, you can
   copy the external programs to a place of your choice
   and tell Peperoni the path of this directory explicitly.

   - Uncheck checkbox @{b}Program in command path@{ub}
     => String gadget and button below are activated
   - Select directory. Options:
     · Click button below (pops up a filerequester)
       and select directory using the filerequester
     · Type in the complete path into the string gadget
       (inlcude device name, but exclude the program's
       file name)

@endnode

@node "KOMPRATE" "Set LZX/ZIP Compression Rate"
@next "PACKEN"
@prev "EXTPROGPFAD"

 @{b}Set LZX/ZIP Compression Rate@{ub}
 ============================

 -- Page «Programs», sections «LZX»/«ZIP»

 The packing formats LZX and ZIP offer compression rate
 setup for packing. The better an archive is compressed,
 the less disk space it needs and the longer the packing
 procedure takes.
 Setup works the same way for both packing formats, you
 just have to use the interface elements in the appropriate
 section.

 @{b}· Set Compression Rate@{ub}

   Provided compression rates are «Good», «Normal» (LZX
   only), «Fast», and «None». «None» just adds all files
   together to a single one without reducing disk space
   usage.

   - Set cycle gadget @{b}Compression rate@{ub} to the
     desired level

@endnode


@node "PACKEN" "Packing Files"
@next "ENTPACKEN"
@prev "VOREINST"

 @{b}5.3 Packing Files@{ub}
 =================

 1. @{"Select" link "MARKIEREN" 0} the files to be packed
 2. Drag selected files onto the packing AppIcon and drop
    them

 @{b}What will happen:@{ub}
 · Destination will be set automatically or will be
   requested via file requester--according to your personal
   settings
 · Packing format will be set automatically or will be
   requested--according to your personal settings
 · Progress window pops up showing the name of the file
   currently under process and a gauge representing the
   proportional amount of files already processed.

   You may abort the procedure by clicking the «Abort»
   button, but it will only stop after the current file has
   been processed completely. The resulting archive will be
   valid anyway.

 @{b}What is going to be created:@{ub}
 If you set the packing destination to «Always ask» in the
 preferences, then you will be able to specify a file name
 for the archive in the file requester. Otherwise, or if you
 leave it blank, the archive's name will be «Archive» by
 default. A suffix representing the packing format will be
 appended, too («.lha», «.lzx», «.zip»).

 If the file «Archive» plus suffix already exists, the new
 one will get a number appended in ascending order (for
 example «Archive1.lha»).

 If you specify the name of an already existing archive,
 the files dropped on the AppIcon will be added to the
 existing archive.

@endnode

@node "ENTPACKEN" "Depacking Files"
@next "BEENDEN"
@prev "PACKEN"

 @{b}5.4 Depacking Files@{ub}
 ===================

 @{b}CAUTION!@{ub}
 Under certain circumstances, this function will overwrite
 existing files without warning. Before starting the
 depacking procedure, check whether there are files in
 the destination having the same names as files in the
 archive. Start depacking only if you are sure that those
 files may be overwritten. If in doubt, create a new empty
 directory and select it as destination.

 1. @{"Select" link "MARKIEREN" 0} archive(s) to be depacked.
 2. Drag selected archive(s) onto the depacking AppIcon and
    drop it/them there.

 @{b}What will happen:@{ub}
 · Destination will be set automatically or will be
   requested via file requester--according to your personal
   settings
 · Archive will be checked for its packing format
 · Progress window pops up showing the name of the archive
   currently under process and a gauge representing the
   proportional amount of archives already processed.

   You may abort the procedure by clicking the «Abort»
   button, but it will only stop after the current archive
   has been processed completely.

 @{b}What is going to be created:@{ub}
 The decompressed files will be written into the destination
 directory. If the archive contains path information and you
 activate the option «Depack complete paths» in the
 preferences, the files will be created within their original
 directory structure.

@endnode

@node "BEENDEN" "Quitting the Program"
@next "PROBLEME"
@prev "ENTPACKEN"

 @{b}5.5 Quitting the Program@{ub}
 ========================

 You may quit Peperoni only with the preferences window
 being open.

 1. Open @{"preferences window" link "VOREINST" 0}

 There are three different ways of quitting:

 · Select menu «Project», item «Quit»
 · Press key combination <right Amiga + Q>
 · Click button «Quit» or press its key shortcut
   (underlined letter)


 The following actions will not quit the program but close
 the preferences window:

 · Press «Esc» key
 · Click the window's close gadget
 · Click one of the buttons «Save», «Use», or «Cancel»
 
@endnode

@node "PROBLEME" "Problems"
@next "ZUKUNFT"
@prev "BEENDEN"

 @{b}6 Known Problems@{ub}
 ================

 @{b}Packing LHA writes paths into the archive@{ub}
 Although you deactivated the option «Pack complete paths»,
 the path information is stored into the new archive.

 Cause:
   Peperoni calls LHA with the «-r» option for recursive
   directory handling which automatically switches on path
   storage.

   Help:
   Copy the files to be packed into «RAM:» and drag the
   copied ones onto the packing AppIcon.

 @{b}LZX archives are not depacked@{ub}
 The option «Depack complete paths» is deactivated, and
 depacking LZX archives has no result.

 Cause:
   You probably use LZX version 1.20 or older. There is
   a bug concerning depacking without paths. Instead
   of depacking, LZX just tests the archive's integrity.
   This bug has been removed since version 1.21.

   Help:
   Get the latest version of LZX and install it.

 @{b}The progress indicator does not work@{ub}
 Yes it does! Right, here comes the description: The
 progress window is opened, but the gauge stays at 0% for
 all the time.

 Cause:
   The gauge does only count the proportional amount of
   files already processed, which means if you drag&drop
   only one single file, the gauge will jump from 0 to
   100% at once as soon as the file has been processed
   entirely. As the progress window is closed in the same
   moment, you won't see the jump.

   Help:
   Drag&drop four or five files at once onto an AppIcon
   and be amazed seeing the gauge working.

@endnode

@node "ZUKUNFT" "The Future"
@next "GESCHICHTE"
