@node "DRAGDROP" "Drag&Drop"

 @{b}The Drag&Drop mechanism@{ub}
 =======================

 Graphical-oriented operating systems offer a way to
 manipulate objects by selecting and moving them around.
 Drag&Drop is just the marketing-oriented name for this
 actually simple mechanism of selecting icons and text with
 the mouse and dragging these items to a particular place
 which holds a specific function. Example: Copying files on
 the Amiga's workbench has always been Drag&Drop.

@endnode

@node "APPICON" "AppIcons"

 @{b}The AppIcon mechanism@{ub}
 =====================

 Standard icons represent actual files on a data medium.
 Therefore they offer actions like copy, execute, and move.
 In addition to these file icons, AmigaOS offers so-called
 AppIcons which are created by running applications and
 react if you double-click them or drop other icons. These
 AppIcons are not actually physically present somewhere on
 the data medium but they are hooked into the system
 temporarily as long as the application runs. They may only
 appear on the Workbench. The look of AppIcons depends on
 how they are implemented. Some programmers tend to build
 the pictures right into the source code, making it nearly
 impossible for users to change the look.

@endnode

@node "AUFRUFEN" "Starting Peperoni via Shell"

 @{b}Calling Peperoni@{ub}
 ================

 @{b}IMPORTANT!@{ub}
 Setting the application's stack too small will most
 certainly make your machine crash. You must set the stack
 to a reasonable size (8192 bytes is sufficient).

 In addition to the graphical user interface of the AmigaOS,
 the workbench, there is a textual-oriented interface: the
 command line interface (CLI or shell). By default, it's
 placed in the system directory »SYS:System/Shell«.

 1. Start shell
 2. Change to Peperoni's home directory:
	@{b}cd@{ub} <directory>
 3. Set up stack size:
	@{b}stack 8192@{ub}
 4. Start Peperoni:
	@{b}Peperoni@{ub}

@endnode

@node "TOOLTYPES" "Supported Tooltypes"

 @{b}Supported Tooltypes@{ub}
 ===================

 · The «|» sign separates a variety of possible values
 · <path> stands for path information which has to be
   enclosed by quotation marks («"»)--otherwise you
   may get problems with path names containing space
   characters (such as «Ram Disk:»).

 @{b}PACK=SAME|ASK|DIR@{ub}
    Destination for packing

 @{b}PACKPATH="@{ub}<pfad>@{b}"@{ub}
    Default packing destination directory (if PACK=DIR)

 @{b}DEPACK=SAME|ASK|DIR@{ub}
    Destination for depacking

 @{b}DEPACKPATH="@{ub}<pfad>@{b}"@{ub}
    Default depacking destination directory (if DEPACK=DIR)

 @{b}APP1PATH="@{ub}<pfad>@{b}"@{ub}
    Path and file name of the packing AppIcon's icon file

 @{b}APP2PATH="@{ub}<pfad>@{b}"@{ub}
    Path and file name of the depacking AppIcon's icon file

 @{b}APP1LABEL="@{ub}<bezeichnung>@{b}"@{ub}
    Label for the packing AppIcon (max. 30 characters)

 @{b}APP2LABEL="@{ub}<bezeichnung>@{b}"@{ub}
    Label for the depacking AppIcon (max. 30 characters)

 @{b}APP1XPOS=@{ub}<koordinate>
    The packing AppIcon's x-coordinate

 @{b}APP1YPOS=@{ub}<koordinate>
    The packing AppIcon's y-coordinate

 @{b}APP2XPOS=@{ub}<koordinate>
    The depacking AppIcon's x-coordinate

 @{b}APP2YPOS=@{ub}<koordinate>
    The depacking AppIcon's y-coordinate

 @{b}PACKFULL=TRUE|FALSE@{ub}
    Store paths when packing?

 @{b}DEPACKFULL=TRUE|FALSE@{ub}
    Restore paths when depacking?

 @{b}LHAC=TRUE|FALSE@{ub}
    LHA located in command path?

 @{b}LHAPATH="@{ub}<pfad>@{b}"@{ub}
    LHA's home directory (if LHA=FALSE)

 @{b}LZXC=TRUE|FALSE@{ub}
    LZX located in command path?

 @{b}LZXPATH="@{ub}<verzeichnis>@{b}"@{ub}
    LZX's home directory (if LZXC=FALSE)

 @{b}LZXRATE=GOOD|NORMAL|FAST|NONE@{ub}
    Compression rate when packing LZX

 @{b}ZIPC=TRUE|FALSE@{ub}
    ZIP located in command path?

 @{b}ZIPPATH="@{ub}<verzeichnis>@{b}"@{ub}
    ZIP's home directory (if ZIPC=FALSE)

 @{b}ZIPRATE=GOOD|FAST|NONE@{ub}
    Compression rate for packing ZIP

 @{b}UNZIPC=TRUE|FALSE@{ub}
    UNZIP located in command path?

 @{b}UNZIPPATH="@{ub}<verzeichnis>@{b}"@{ub}
    UNZIP's home directory (if UNZIPC=FALSE)

@endnode

